affic control and rate limiting. Additionally, I'll integrate immutable audit logging and SIEM. Finally, I will address enterprise secrets management and deployment configuration using IaC.\n\n\n**Comparing Security Architectures**\n\nI'm now generating an ASCII diagram contrasting Phase 5's local sandbox with Phase 6's production-grade architecture, emphasizing trust boundaries, TLS channels, and data flow. Furthermore, I'll document a detailed enterprise audit, highlighting Phase 5's security boundaries and the roadmap for Phase 6 hardening. The \"Secured Sandbox & The Enterprise Fortress\" visual metaphor will guide the layout.\n\n\n**Verifying Documentation Format**\n\nI'm now focused on the Markdown structure for `docs/PHASE_5_SECURITY_LIMITATIONS.md`, aiming for superior readability. This involves clean headings, warning blockquotes, bullet points, code snippets, and an ASCII architecture diagram. I will ensure mobile-friendliness and focus on cognitive readability. I've confirmed I am following the instructions for file changes and not touching other files. I'll thoroughly document the MVP security limitations.\n\n\n**Documenting Comprehensive Security**\n\nI'm now detailing the full scope of Phase 6 hardening, encompassing all twelve limitations and the ten required steps. My current focus is on clearly documenting the architectural responses and reasoning behind each item in the document. I will incorporate all of the aspects including the lack of MFA, refresh token hardening, httpOnly secure cookie implementation, rate limiting, and the audit-grade logs. Finally, I will address secrets management, the deployment configuration, and CORS hardening. I'll meticulously structure the Markdown file for clarity.\n\n\n"}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T19:29:45.368Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"tool","toolName":"editor","toolCallId":"muv0j9de","input":{"path":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/docs/PHASE_5_SECURITY_LIMITATIONS.md","old_text":null,"new_text":"# GFF AI Platform: Phase 5 Security Limitations & Phase 6 Hardening Roadmap\n\nThis document serves as the official **Enterprise Security Audit and Risk Assessment** for **Phase 5** of the GFF AI Platform. It provides a transparent, honest, and rigorous evaluation of the current MVP’s security limitations and outlines the explicit architectural requirements for **Phase 6 Enterprise Security Hardening**.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Security Philosophy & The Local Sandbox Metaphor\n\nIn alignment with the GFF AI **Sovereign Operating System** architecture, the Phase 5 release is designed exclusively as a **local developer sandbox, high-fidelity presentation prototype, and demonstration environment**. \n\nTo optimize developer ergonomics, reduce evaluation friction, and enable offline-first demonstrations, certain enterprise-grade security protocols have been deferred or simplified. While the user interface models perfect-fidelity access patterns, MFA dialogs, and compliance logs, the underlying execution engine runs within a defined **Local Boundary**.\n\n```\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n|                              PHASE 5 SECURITY BOUNDARY                            |\n|                                                                                   |\n|  [ NEXT.JS FRONTEND ] <=========( Local Loopback HTTP )==========> [ FASTAPI MVP ]  |\n|          |                                                              |         |\n|   (localStorage)                                                    (dev.db)      |\n|          |                                                              |         |\n|     JWT Session                                                      SQLite3      |\n|                                                                                   |\n|  * Strictly isolated to localhost.                                                 |\n|  * Intended only for local demonstration, offline audits, and validation.         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n```\n\nThis document establishes a clear separation between the **Phase 5 Sandbox** and the **Phase 6 Production Target** to ensure that compliance officers, CISOs, and enterprise architects can safely plan their sovereign deployments.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Phase 5 MVP Security Limitations (An Honest Evaluation)\n\nBelow is an exhaustive matrix of the technical security limitations present in the Phase 5 local MVP backend. These compromises are typical for local evaluation and rapid prototyping phases, but must be mitigated before any public or production hosting.\n\n### 2.1. Client-Side Authentication Token Storage (JWT)\n*   **Current State**: Access tokens generated by the FastAPI backend are stored in the client's web browser using `localStorage` or development-only memory states.\n*   **Security Implication**: Storage via `localStorage` is vulnerable to **Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)** attacks. If a malicious script is executed in the user's browser context (e.g., via a compromised third-party package dependency), the token can be read directly by client-side JavaScript.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Acceptable only because the sandbox is run in isolated local host environments (`localhost:3000`) where external script injections are highly controlled.\n\n### 2.2. Persistence Engine (Local SQLite DB)\n*   **Current State**: Data is stored inside a single local SQLite file (`dev.db`) within the backend directory.\n*   **Security Implication**: SQLite does not support robust concurrent user lock patterns, lacks granular row-level security policies (RLS), does not natively encrypt records at rest without specialized extensions (such as SQLCipher), and lacks high-availability (HA) database clustering.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Ideal for zero-dependency local setups (runs immediately without Docker or external DB servers) but vulnerable to data loss or file corruption in production high-load environments.\n\n### 2.3. Identity Bootstrapping (Local Seed Users)\n*   **Current State**: System administrative and client-tenant credentials are bootstrapped via a local seeder file (`app/seed.py`) with pre-configured developer passwords hashed using standard bcrypt algorithms.\n*   **Security Implication**: Shared seed credentials and static administrative initial states exist inside public Git repositories for local evaluation. Leaving these unchanged exposes systems to instant compromise.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Local developer accounts are strictly for offline demonstration and testing.\n\n### 2.4. Lack of Production Password Reset Loops\n*   **Current State**: There is no live SMTP or transactional email delivery service integrated. Triggering a password reset process only simulates a cryptographic operation on the client interface without delivering a verified token.\n*   **Security Implication**: Users cannot recover lost credentials securely. Any reset attempt lacks server-side verification loops, token expiration tracking, or IP-based rate protection.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: The system relies on manually updating or resetting the SQLite user table locally.\n\n### 2.5. Simulated Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)\n*   **Current State**: The Multi-Factor Authentication / One-Time Password (MFA/OTP) screen simulates state-of-the-art cryptographic sequence rotations and streams live diagnostic eBPF logs. However, it does not perform server-side verification of TOTP algorithms.\n*   **Security Implication**: The security benefit of 2FA/MFA is bypassed at the API level during the MVP phase.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Implemented purely for visual and user-experience validation to show clients how premium security overrides will function in the final product.\n\n### 2.6. Absence of Refresh Token Hardening & Rotation\n*   **Current State**: The system utilizes a single-tier JWT access token with a long expiration duration (8 days/11520 minutes configured in `.env` for developer convenience). There are no secure refresh tokens, rotation mechanisms, or active blacklists.\n*   **Security Implication**: If a session JWT is intercepted or leaked, the attacker gains unrestricted access for the entire lifecycle of the token (8 days) with no server-side capability to revoke individual active sessions.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Maximizes convenience for developers testing flows without constant re-authentication.\n\n### 2.7. Session Transport Strategy (No httpOnly Cookies)\n*   **Current State**: Secure session transport has not been enforced. JWTs are passed directly via authorization headers from the browser's storage rather than transmitted via secure, browser-managed cookies.\n*   **Security Implication**: Standard browser header injection does not benefit from native web-browser protections against cross-site leakage or session hijacking.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Standard local REST API implementation pattern.\n\n### 2.8. Lack of Perimeter Protection & Rate Limiting\n*   **Current State**: The FastAPI MVP has no middleware limits on requests per second, IP restriction gates, or brute-force dictionary attack protections.\n*   **Security Implication**: Malicious actors could easily execute denial-of-service (DDoS) requests or run rapid credential stuffing attacks against the `/token` endpoint to compromise seed accounts.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Relying strictly on local developer isolation to protect API endpoints.\n\n### 2.9. Audit-Grade Logging & Log Immutability\n*   **Current State**: System activity, model runs, and administration operations are written to standard terminal standard outputs (Stdout) and basic local SQLite audit tables.\n*   **Security Implication**: Local logs are mutable (can be easily deleted or edited by any user with access to the `dev.db` file) and do not support structured JSON telemetry required by modern SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) collectors.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Logs are designed for immediate developer diagnostics, not compliance forensic auditing.\n\n### 2.10. Non-Hardened Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)\n*   **Current State**: Basic role routing and decorator security checks ensure standard frontend navigation safety. However, a comprehensive, formal security audit of RBAC execution layers and API endpoints has not been performed.\n*   **Security Implication**: Potential exists for \"broken object-level authorization\" (BOLA) or privilege escalation if endpoints are accessed directly via raw API requests with manipulated tenant IDs.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Focused on simulating the visual states of 7 core roles.\n\n### 2.11. Absence of File Scanning & Malware Filtering\n*   **Current State**: The portal's secure legal vault and document indexing systems simulate sovereign compliance. When files are uploaded in the sandbox, they bypass physical antivirus or malware scanners.\n*   **Security Implication**: Uploading infected PDF/Word documents could expose admin users or automated parse agents to security vulnerabilities when files are fetched or processed.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Completely offline-safe since uploaded assets are only mocked in browser-side execution contexts.\n\n### 2.12. Zero Payment Compliance Integration\n*   **Current State**: Dynamic billing ledgers, SLA logs, and consumption invoices are calculated dynamically via database seeds. No actual integrations exist with payment providers (such as Stripe) or PCI-DSS auditing structures.\n*   **Security Implication**: The billing system is not designed to hold live banking, credit card, or payment routing keys, and does not comply with international financial security standards.\n*   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Intended strictly for operational and compute cost simulation.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Phase 6 Enterprise Security Hardening Roadmap\n\nTo prepare the GFF AI Platform for enterprise deployment and strict compliance certifications (such as SOC 2 Type II, ISO/IEC 27001:2022, and GDPR/HIPAA enclaves), the following hardening roadmap is established. \n\n```\n+----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n|                                    PHASE 6 HARDENED PRODUCTION TARGET                                    |\n|                                                                                                          |\n|  [ SECURE CLIENTS ] =====( TLS 1.3 / strict HSTS )=====> [ AWS WAF / Perimeter Gate ]                    |\n|                                                                 |                                        |\n|                                                     [ SECURE REVERSE PROXY / CORS ]                      |\n|                                                                 |                                        |\n|  [ FRONTEND ENGINE ] ===( httpOnly / Secure Cookie )===> [ FASTAPI CLUSTERED APPS ]                     |\n|                                                                 |                                        |\n|                                                       ( AWS KMS AES-256 Encryption )                     |\n|                                                       ( AWS Secrets Manager, IAM Roles )                 |\n|                                                                 |                                        |\n|                                                      [ RDS POSTGRESQL MULTI-AZ ]                         |\n+----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n```\n\n### 3.1. Production-Grade Persistence Engine\n*   **Action Plan**: Migrate the database storage engine from a local SQLite file to a managed, high-availability PostgreSQL cluster (e.g., **AWS Aurora Serverless v2** or **Azure Database for PostgreSQL**).\n*   **Security Protocols**:\n    *   Deploy the database cluster exclusively inside **Private Subnets** within an enterprise Virtual Private Cloud (VPC), blocking direct public internet access.\n    *   Enforce **Encryption-at-Rest** using AWS KMS (AES-256) keys.\n    *   Enable SSL/TLS certificates for all SQL connections.\n    *   Utilize PostgreSQL **Row-Level Security (RLS)** to enforce absolute multi-tenant data segregation.\n\n### 3.2. Hardened Cookie-Based Session Storage\n*   **Action Plan**: Transition from `localStorage` token storage to a server-managed, cookie-based session transport strategy.\n*   **Security Protocols**:\n    *   Store JWTs or Session IDs inside standard HTTP cookies.\n    *   Configure cookie headers with strict defense flags:\n        *   `HttpOnly`: Prevents client-side scripts (JavaScript) from accessing the session token, completely neutralizing XSS-based token theft.\n        *   `Secure`: Forces the browser to transmit cookies exclusively over encrypted HTTPS/TLS connections.\n        *   `SameSite=Strict` or `SameSite=Lax`: Mitigates **Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)** vulnerabilities by restricting cookie transmission on cross-origin requests.\n\n### 3.3. Refresh Token Rotation (RTR)\n*   **Action Plan**: Implement a dual-token authentication system using a short-lived Access Token (e.g., 15 minutes) and a hardened Refresh Token stored securely in a redis-backed fast session database.\n*   **Security Protocols**:\n    *   **Rotation**: Every time a client requests a new access token using a refresh token, a new refresh token is issued, and the previous token is immediately invalidated.\n    *   **Replay Attack Detection**: If a used or old refresh token is presented, the system flags a high-priority security anomaly, invalidates the entire active session family, and forces immediate re-authentication.\n\n### 3.4. Enterprise Password Recovery Loop\n*   **Action Plan**: Deploy a fully secured transactional email pipeline utilizing enterprise gateways (e.g., AWS SES, SendGrid, or Mailgun).\n*   **Security Protocols**:\n    *   Generate cryptographically secure, high-entropy, short-lived reset tokens (expiring in 15 minutes).\n    *   Transmit reset links via HTTPS.\n    *   Ensure the password reset API does not disclose user existence (preventing account enumeration attacks).\n    *   Record and log password update events within the audit trail.\n\n### 3.5. Production Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) & Enterprise SSO\n*   **Action Plan**: Replace the high-fidelity MFA simulations with real server-side cryptographic verification and Enterprise Single Sign-On (SSO) systems.\n*   **Security Protocols**:\n    *   **TOTP Verification**: Implement standard server-side verification using standard algorithms (RFC 6238) compatible with Google Authenticator, Microsoft Authenticator, or Bitwarden.\n    *   **Federated Identity**: Integrate SAML 2.0 / OpenID Connect (OIDC) protocols to support corporate identity providers (such as Okta, Microsoft Entra ID / Active Directory, Ping Identity, and Duo).\n\n### 3.6. Network-Level Traffic Control & Rate Limiting\n*   **Action Plan**: Introduce application-level and network-level perimeter protections.\n*   **Security Protocols**:\n    *   Deploy **FastAPI-Limiter** on all sensitive backend API endpoints (specifically `/token`, login gates, and document ingest points) powered by Redis token-bucket mechanics.\n    *   Position the platform behind global Web Application Firewalls (such as **Cloudflare Enterprise** or **AWS WAF**) to block SQL injections, cross-site scripting payloads, and malicious bot traffic.\n    *   Implement smart IP throttling, rate thresholds, and temporary quarantine zones for suspicious client networks.\n\n### 3.7. Immutable Audit Logging & SIEM Integration\n*   **Action Plan**: Standardize all logging to write structured, machine-readable JSON payloads containing ISO 8601 timestamps, actor IDs, client tenant contexts, and exact API parameters.\n*   **Security Protocols**:\n    *   Stream log output in real time to external cloud aggregators (e.g., **AWS CloudWatch Logs**, **Datadog**, or **Splunk**).\n    *   Configure log storage with write-once-read-many (WORM) configurations, ensuring logs cannot be modified, deleted, or corrupted, satisfying SOC 2 forensic auditing criteria.\n    *   Establish high-severity alerts for abnormal behaviors (e.g., mass document downloads, administrative role swaps, or unauthorized login attempts).\n\n### 3.8. Enterprise Secrets Management\n*   **Action Plan**: Completely eliminate environment variable declarations of sensitive credentials inside local files, code repositories, or static server configurations.\n*   **Security Protocols**:\n    *   Integrate the backend with dedicated key vaults such as **AWS Secrets Manager**, **HashiCorp Vault**, or **Azure Key Vault**.\n    *   Enable automatic, scheduled rotation of database credentials, third-party API keys, and JWT cryptographic signing secrets.\n    *   Restrict access to key vaults using fine-grained IAM resource policies.\n\n### 3.9. Secure Deployment Configuration & IaC Hardening\n*   **Action Plan**: Package the entire system into secure, lightweight Docker containers and orchestrate deployments via **AWS ECS (Fargate)** or Kubernetes (**AWS EKS**).\n*   **Security Protocols**:\n    *   Construct Dockerfiles using slim, non-root base images, ensuring processes do not run with root permissions inside the container.\n    *   Utilize Infrastructure-as-Code (IaC) tools (e.g., **Terraform**) to configure networks, enforcing private subnets, secure security groups, and disabling public IPv4 addresses on execution nodes.\n    *   Mandate **TLS 1.3** across all load balancers with automated HTTPS certificate renewals.\n\n### 3.10. Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) Hardening\n*   **Action Plan**: Remove any generic or wildcard declarations (`*`) from CORS origins in production configuration files.\n*   **Security Protocols**:\n    *   Establish strict whitelist parameters mapping exclusively to certified, company-owned corporate domains (e.g., `https://portal.gff.ai` and `https://admin.gff.ai`).\n    *   Enforce HTTP header protections, including:\n        *   `Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS)`\n        *   `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`\n        *   `X-Frame-Options: DENY` (to prevent clickjacking)\n        *   `Content-Security-Policy (CSP)` (to explicitly whitelist allowed script domains and disable inline scripts).\n\n---\n\n## 4. Compliance Goal Tracking Matrix\n\nThe transition from Phase 5 to Phase 6 is engineered to align directly with major global compliance frameworks. The table below highlights how the planned hardening steps fulfill key control requirements.\n\n| Compliance Framework | Target Control | Phase 5 MVP Status | Phase 6 Production Remediation Plan |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **SOC 2 Type II** | CC6.1 - Access Transmission | ⚠️ Partial (Plain headers over HTTP localhost) | Complete (TLS 1.3, HttpOnly/Secure cookies, HSTS) |\n| **SOC 2 Type II** | CC6.3 - Role-Based Access | ⚠️ Basic (Frontend-focused simulated routing) | Complete (Strict endpoint decorators with RLS PostgreSQL) |\n| **ISO 27001:2022** | A.8.20 - Network Security | ❌ No active network rate limits / WAF | Complete (AWS WAF, FastAPI token-bucket limits via Redis) |\n| **ISO 27001:2022** | A.8.12 - Log Auditing | ⚠️ Partial (Mutable local SQLite tables / Stdout) | Complete (Immutable logs streaming to SIEM / CloudWatch) |\n| **HIPAA Security** | 164.312(a)(2)(iv) - Encrypt | ❌ SQLite unencrypted by default | Complete (AWS KMS AES-256 encrypted Aurora storage) |\n| **PCI-DSS 4.0** | Req 8.3 - Secure Passwords | ⚠️ Basic (Standard local bcrypt without complexity) | Complete (Okta SSO, enterprise complexity controls, MFA) |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Summary Conclusion\n\nThe Phase 5 Local MVP Backend provides a secure, fully functional, and highly visual sandbox to validate GFF AI's sovereign workflows. By isolating execution to `localhost` and explicitly documenting the trade-offs above, we preserve developer productivity while establishing a flawless, production-ready blueprint for Phase 6.\n\nPrior to migrating this codebase to public servers or connecting live customer data, engineering teams **must** execute the hardening steps listed in Section 3 to ensure full operational sovereignty and data security.\n","insert_line":null}}}
